observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Direct the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC) and Municipal Engineer to, at the beginning of the year, submit to this Office the list of all ongoing government Programs/Projects/ Activities (PPAs) and those that are to be implemented during the year;

Display project sign boards at the project location and inform this Office within ten (10) days after the award of the infrastructure project or before the start of the program/activity that the appropriate project signboards and/or public notices are already posted.

We recommended the management the following:

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to effect the immediate termination of its depository accounts in the PNB, Iligan Branch, and transfer the balance of the fund to any AGDBs located in the nearest area of jurisdiction, and to refrain from opening new accounts with PNB; 

To strictly follow the DOF Memorandum Order for the safety, security, and convenience of all the LGUs.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
Create an inventory committee headed by the GSO to conduct an actual physical inventory taking of all properties of the Municipality to establish the accuracy, existence, and completeness of the reported PPE in the financial statements;
Instruct the inventory committee thru the GSO that if no records could be found, start recording the actual existence of buildings, equipment, motor vehicles, furniture and fixtures by office, and if possible, reconstruct the records;
Direct the GSO to:
Assign property number for each PPE item (Property Sticker);
Prepare a separate report on unserviceable properties, plant and equipment and facilitate the preparation of Inspection and Inventory Report;
Update the property records based on the results of the physical inventory and reconcile with accounting records to come up with the reconciled balances of PPE accounts to be considered as the correct balance of the agency's PPE;
Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary adjustments on the deficiencies noted based on the result of the actual inventory taking;
Furnish the COA Audit Team with a copy of the Updated Inventory Report and/ or Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant, and Equipment (RPCPPE); and
Ensure strict adherence to the above stated laws, rules, and regulations.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
Require the GSO to:
Maintain Property Cards (PC) for the PPE to account for the receipt and disposition;
Ensure that the deliveries of properties and equipment are immediately recorded in the Property Cards (PC) based on the AIR and other supporting documents;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Make reconciliation with inventory reports, property cards, and subsidiary ledgers;
Ensure that the deliveries of properties and equipment are immediately recorded in the PPE Subsidiary Ledger Cards based on the AIR and other supporting documents; and
Ensure strict adherence to the above-stated laws, rules, and regulations.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
Ensure that the Municipal Engineer has provided the local accountant and the general services officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;
Direct the General Services Officer to:
Maintain the Local Road Inventory and Road Map, and to keep a complete Local Road Network Property Cards for each local road and its components and
Reconcile the total amount of local roads recognized in the Report on Local Road Network with that of the total amount presented in the FS;
Create and direct the Inventory Committee to conduct an annual physical count of the road networks and prepare the Report on the Physical Count of the Local Road Networks; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to:
Keep and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network (Local Road Network Ledger Card) and prepare a lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each component at the end of the year;
Disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements the total road network system following the format provided in Annex B of COA Circular No. 2015-008; and
Reconcile the total amount of local roads presented in the FS with the records of the GSO.

We have recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
a. Direct the Municipal Assessor and the Municipal Treasurer to fast track the completion of updates on the assessment roll and the Real Property Tax Account Register/Certified List of Taxpayers, and submit the latter to the Office of the Municipal Accountant;
b. Based on the list, direct the Municipal Accountant-Designate to take up in the books, the RPT/SET Receivable account to establish a realistic collection target on Real Property Tax. Also, the corresponding subsidiary ledger shall be maintained to monitor tax collections and delinquencies; 
c. Direct the OIC-Municipal Treasurer to develop an effective tax collection campaign and offering of incentives of full payment of tax dues in order to increase collection of real property taxes. For delinquent real property taxes, impose the remedies provided for in the Local Government Code; and
d. Direct the OIC-Municipal Treasurer to ensure timely reconciliation of the Municipality’s RPT records with the Province.

We have recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:

a. To strictly adhere to the provisions of Section 337 of Republic Act No. 7160 and to strengthen its control over cash; 
b. Direct the OIC-Municipal Treasurer to ensure that the cash overdraft incurred in the General Fund at year end will be adequately covered with the first collections of the immediately succeeding fiscal year in accordance with Section 337 of R.A No. 7160;
c. Require the OIC-Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant-Designate to  strictly limit the disbursements of funds to valid obligations only as appropriated in the approved Annual Budget in order to avoid incurrence of any cash overdraft at year-end; and 
d. Require the OIC-Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant-Designate to ensure that Cashbook-Cash in Bank/ Cash-in-Bank general ledger are updated and balanced daily/monthly in order to avoid incurring negative balances and bank service charges (penalty) for issuing checks without sufficient fund.

We have recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
a. Ensure strict compliance with laws, rules and regulations on the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advance pursuant to Section 89 of P.D No. 1445, and pertinent Sections of COA Circular No. 97-002; 
b. Direct the Municipal Accountant to see to it that cash advances are supported with the necessary documents, and additional cash advance for the same purpose shall be granted after previous cash advance is liquidated, or proper accounting thereof is made;
c. Direct the OIC-Municipal Treasurer to stop the payment of reimbursements through his cash advance, reimbursement is discouraged as mode of payment for LGU’s expenses; and also, payment to suppliers is made thru checks. And follow Republic Act 9184 in all procurement of goods;
d. Stop the grant of cash advance to elective officials for expenses other than for their travelling expenses; and
e. Designate another disbursing officer in order to decrease the volume of the cash advance of the OIC-Municipal Treasurer.

We have recommended to the Local Chief Executive to direct the Municipal Environment and Natural Resources Officer to:

a. For monitoring purposes, update the Office of the Auditor on the status of the approval process of the municipality’s 10-year Solid Waste Management Plan (SWMP) for the year 2019-2028, and submit copy thereof once the plan is approved by the SNW Commission;
b. Review and update the plan  as required by law to ensure its sustainability, relevance and effectiveness;
c. Ensure that campaigns should be collaborated with the barangay officials concerned; and
d. Continued and stricter implementation of waste segregation, and thorough collection of waste based on set schedules.

